Section 1: Understanding the DataSet (Overview) - EDA¶

Problem Definition¶

  • Given data containing the "different attributes of used cars sold in different locations,"
    • derive insights from the data
    • predict the prices of used cars (linear Regression model)
    • communicate recommendations that will help the business

Initial Observations¶

  • S. No.: (Seriel Number) appears to have no null values; it is an integer; Seriel number appears to match the row index number
  • Name: (Name of car) appears to be categorical yet current data type is object; contains 2 pieces of information (brand name and model name); appears to have no missing values; consider splitting the data and categorizing
  • Location: (where the car is being sold) appears to have no missing values; iiss a object type that posibly should change to category
  • Year: (Manufacturing year of car) appears to have no missing values; data type is integer
  • Kilometers_driven: (total distance drive in kilometers): data type is integer; appears to contain no missing values
  • Fuel_Type: (has the following categories (according to problem statement) Petrol, Diesel, electric, CNG, LPG; appears to contain no missing values; currently dtype object - consider changintto categorical
  • Transmission: (either Automatic or Manual) - currently object dtype - consider changing to categorical; appears to contain no missing values
  • Owner_Type: Appears to be a cardinal value perhaps representing number of previous owners; appears to contain no missing values; currently an object dtype that might need to be a category
  • Millege: (Standard manufacturer declared mileage in km/kg) appears to contain 2 missing values which willneed to imputed or dropped;currently object dtype with units; units will likely be dropped and dtype converted to float
  • Engine: (displacement volume of the engine in CC); currently an object dtype containing the units; likely need to drop the units and change the dtype to float; currently contains few missing values
  • Power: (max power of he engine in bhp) currently an object dtype containing the units;likely need to drop the units and change the dtype to float; currently contains many missing values
  • Seats: (number of seats in car) is currently a float dtype (which might be changes to category); contains few missing
  • New_Price: (price of new car/same model in INR Lakhs); apppears to contain no missing values and has dtype of float64 which is appropriate for data;
  • Price: (Price of the used car in INR Lakhs): target variable; dtype is float64 which is appropriate; appears to contain many missing values whose corresponding rows will need to be dropped

Observations¶

  • S.No: is a series of numbers 1 to 7253 on a scale of 1. This value will likely be uniformative for the model.
  • Year: 50% of the values of Year are integers between 2014 and 2019, inclusively. The data is heavily skewed left with many outliers betweeen 1995 and 2005.
  • Kilometers_Driven: Has a max value of 6,500,000. This value is suspect based on domain knowledge of the maximum number of miles that a car can be drive in its lifetime. This value is also an outlier. Likely this value needs to be dropped.
  • Seats - Seats appears to be a categorical variable with a mode of 5 (Q1=Median=Q3 = 5);

EDA Summary¶

Data Descriptions¶

  • The target variable is Price: dtype is float64
  • Although the Name column is object, the data in the name column can be split to Model name and brand name. These columns will be informative for the model.
  • Some columns, such as mileage, power and engine are objects but only because they contain the units. Once the units are dropped and the dtype changed to float64, these columns will inform the model.
  • The most informative data to predict Price appreaars to be NewPrice.
  • S.NO. is not informative for Price.
  • Columns such as Location, Seats, Fuel_Type, Owner_Type, Transmission are categorical in nature; once changes to category dtype and then converted to dummy variables, they should inform the model.
  • There is a relatively small amount of data which can be imputed so that it is useful.
  • Price has some missing data and since it is the target variable, these rows will be dropped to avoid introducing bias to the model.

Data Cleaning¶

  • Copy dataset (name cars) and preprocess data on copied set
  • New_Price is the target variable
  • S. No: Drop this column as it does not inform the model
  • Name: Split the name column into brand_name nd model_name; change data types to category
  • Location: Change Location to Category
  • Year: Transform Year data to aid with skewness; apply log transformation;
  • Kilometers_Driven: Drop row containing Kilometers_Driven = 6.5 million as this value is both an outlier and unreasonable. Transofrm using MinMix scaling
  • Fuel_Type: change to categorical dtype
  • Transmission: Change from object to categorical dtype
  • Owner_Type: Change from Object to categorical dtype
  • Mileage: drop units from values; change dtype from Object to float; impute missing values with Median; transform data with MinMax scale
  • Engine: Drop the units from the value; change the dtype tp float64; impute missing values; transform data
  • Seats: Change dtype from float64 to category; impute missing values using mode;investigate the car with a seat count of 0 as this outlier does not make sense with respect to the domain
  • Power: Drop Units from column; change dtype of column to float64; imputer missing values with Median; Transform data with log transformation
  • New_Price: no changes needed
  • Price: Target variable; Drop rows with Missing values

#Check Model Performance (using code from Anime Notebook)
# function to compute adjusted R-squared
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


# function to compute MAPE
def mape_score(targets, predictions):
    return np.mean(np.abs(targets - predictions) / targets) * 100


# function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model
def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance

    model: regressor
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)  # to compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)  # to compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # to compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAE
    mape = mape_score(target, pred)  # to compute MAPE

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2,
            "MAPE": mape
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

Model Performance (using Anime case study as a guide for evaluation)¶

The train and test R2 are 0.97 and 0.83, indicating that the model explains 97% and 83% of the total variation in the train and test sets respectively. Also, both scores are comparable. The train and test adjusted R2 values are 0.947 and 3.33, respectively. An adjusted R2 of 3.3 is not reasonable; therefore I will not use these calues to evalute the model. RMSE values on the train and test sets are also comparable and reasonable for this dataset.

The model does not appear to be overfitting.

MAE indicates that our current model is able to predict Price within a mean error of 0.2.16 on the test set. This is reasoanble for the dataset.

MAPE of 37.65 on the test data means that we are able to predict within ~38% of the used car price.

Overall the model could be improved by more feature engineering, that is eliminating certain independent variables are generating new models to see if the model can be improved. Additionally, many numical variables were scaled using log or MinMax scaling. Experimenting with various scales might improve the model. Finally, although outlier detection was performed on numeric variables, it was not investigated for categorical variables. This also might improve the model.

Key Business Takeaways¶

The Linear Regression Model can be used as a predictor of used car prices given the following information about the car: Model Name, Brand Name, Location, Manufacturing year, Kilometers Drive, Fuel Type, Transmission, Owner, standard Mileage, Ownershp type, engine, power, Seats and New_Price. New_Price is the most informative variable for Price.

The business should focus on the variables of New_Price and Location, as well as cars with 5 seats (as these are by far the most popular cars. I would also recommend that the business focus of Diesel or Petrol cars with Manual transmission.
